{
  "texts": [
    "In general, learning a (latent) utility function f from pairwise preferences between objects is called the \"pairwise learning\" approach.",
    "Instead of learning from pointwise or pairwise training data, a latent utility function can also be induced from rankings x 1 x 2.",
    ". x m of any size.",
    "Directly learning from data of that kind (instead of decomposing a ranking into pairwise preferences) is referred to as the \"listwise learning\" approach (Cao et al. 2007).",
    "What this approach requires is a notion of how well a utility function fits an observed ranking."
  ]
}